Attributing a proportion of deaths during a heatwave to climate change requires multiple steps, taking into account that natural climate variability and anthropogenic climate change jointly contribute to the occurrence and intensity of a heatwave. Event attribution is a growing field in climatology that determines whether (and to what extent) an individual event was influenced by anthropogenic forcing of the climate system (
 Easterling et al. 2016; 
 NAS 2016; 
 Stott et al. 2016). Primary approaches include using the observational record to determine the change in probability or magnitude of an event (e.g., 
 Stott et al. 2004; 
 Sch√§r et al. 2004) and using model simulations to compare the the probability of an event occurring with and without anthropogenic climate change (e.g., 
 Hoerling et al. 2013). These provide slightly different information for use in estimating the number of deaths during a heatwave that could be attributed to climate change.
